<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="577" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1289,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1910,1935]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is a reference to the yellow-colored quartz, citrino. The epithet is from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[1365,1435,1911,1934]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">citrus,</emphasis>
pure yellow, in reference to the yellow patches on the ventral wings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1017,1982,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1289,2007]" box="[199,1017,1982,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1982,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is currently known only from its 
<typeStatus box="[872,920,1983,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
