<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="578" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1366,1679]" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1366,1391]" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">Comments.</emphasis>
The arm of the gnathos ribbed at the tip of 
<taxonomicName authority="Siewert &amp; Madruga &amp; Dolibaina &amp; Mielke &amp; Casagrande, 2018" authorityName="Siewert &amp; Madruga &amp; Dolibaina &amp; Mielke &amp; Casagrande" authorityYear="2018" box="[884,1098,1366,1391]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrinus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[884,1098,1366,1391]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">Drephalys citrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1110,1180,1366,1391]" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1110,1180,1366,1391]" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is also present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1942" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heraclides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">D. heraclides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, suggesting the latter is a close relative of the former. 
<taxonomicName authority="Siewert &amp; Madruga &amp; Dolibaina &amp; Mielke &amp; Casagrande, 2018" authorityName="Siewert &amp; Madruga &amp; Dolibaina &amp; Mielke &amp; Casagrande" authorityYear="2018" box="[877,997,1404,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrinus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[877,997,1404,1427]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">D. citrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1004,1068,1402,1427]" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1004,1068,1402,1427]" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, together with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1942" box="[1237,1389,1402,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heraclides">
<emphasis box="[1237,1389,1402,1427]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">D. heraclides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1952" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1952" box="[151,400,1438,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opifex">
<emphasis box="[151,253,1439,1463]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">D. opifex</emphasis>
Evans, 1952
</taxonomicName>
, are the only yellow-checkered species belonging to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson" authorityYear="1893" box="[1138,1254,1438,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1138,1254,1438,1463]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">Drephalys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
without a costal fold on the forewing (
<figureCitation box="[403,473,1474,1499]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1765,1788]" captionTargetBox="[198,1387,221,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[198,1388,198,1717]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Species of Drephalys in dorsal and ventral views. 1–2, D. dracarys sp. n. 3–4, D. electrinus sp. n. 5–6, D. citrinus sp. n." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1440351/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). The absence of the forewing costal fold in this subgenus is also shared by 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1952" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1952" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olva">
<emphasis box="[1352,1436,1474,1499]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">D. olva</emphasis>
Evans, 1952
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1952" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1952" box="[346,600,1510,1535]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olvina">
<emphasis box="[346,451,1510,1535]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">D. olvina</emphasis>
Evans, 1952
</taxonomicName>
, while 
<taxonomicName authority="Burns, 2000" authorityName="Burns" authorityYear="2000" box="[682,946,1510,1535]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Drephalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kidonoi">
<emphasis box="[682,801,1510,1535]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="578">D. kidonoi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[808,946,1511,1535]" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" refId="ref4060" refString="Burns, J. M. &amp; Janzen, D. H. (2000) Drephalys: division of this showy Neotropical genus, plus a new species and the immatures and food plants of two species from Costa Rican dry forest (Hesperiidae: Pyrginae). Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society, 53, 77 - 89." type="journal article">Burns, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has a vestigial costal fold (
<bibRefCitation pageId="5" pageNumber="578" refId="ref4060" refString="Burns, J. M. &amp; Janzen, D. H. (2000) Drephalys: division of this showy Neotropical genus, plus a new species and the immatures and food plants of two species from Costa Rican dry forest (Hesperiidae: Pyrginae). Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society, 53, 77 - 89." type="journal article">Burns &amp; Janzen 2000</bibRefCitation>
). The evaluation of this character is useful to differentiate the males of species with similar wing phenotypes, as is the case with species possessing yellow spots on the dorsal wings. However, studies of other features are required for species-level determinations, such as the development of the ventral hind wing white band and details of the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
